<Author>frenchandparisian
<Content>NO POINT BOOKING ANYWHERE ELSE This august, we did our 2nd and 3rd stay at Hotel Bel Air. My partner, mother-in-law and I had been staying here last year as the highlight of our US vacation, and liked it so much we wanted our sisters to share the experience.It started with on a great note, with the valet parking greeting us from last year, and Roger the bellman starting the conversation where it has stopped last year with my m-i-law, who does not speak a single word of english, let alone understand one.It turned sour when we realized our reservation from march had been messed up : one of our 3 rooms was supposed to be a twin, and was a king. Front desk went all red, apparently very embarassed. But there was no twin available. He explained that the previous guest had staid longer, and our room was not available, which I find unprofessional, unacceptable and none of my business : he should have just lied, and mentionned a fire, a flood, or anything beyond his control. He was apologetic, and as for the requested compensation, asked what time would I like the GM to be in touch with me.Back from dinner, we found that a bottle of champagne, flowers and chocolates had been delivered, only to the wrong room, which when I mentionned to him, he thought was joke. It was not.At 9.00 am the next morning, the GM was on the phone, asking what he could do for me. Hell, just get my reservation right, apart from the fatct that the Gd DL had no patio and was therefore disppointing ! He said that the hotel was booked solid, but the room would be modified accordingly, offered 25% discount on the night where the bed had to be shared, and a downgrade to the next rate for the whole, which I found acceptable.Coming back later in the afternoon, the room had really been modified ; they had changed the King to 2 Twins, and completely changed the decoration around it. Spectacular, it looked like another room.Lather that evening, room service turned up with another bottle of champagne, only vintage this time, and some canap茅s. Only it was once again to the wrong room. Anyway.Apart from this, the forst stay was stellar. Nothing is too much for any of the staff, who are yet totally unobtrusive. The concierge booked us at Spago and also at Geoffrey (Malibu) at last minute notice. We loved every inch of the property, every second of our stay. Loved it actually so much that my partner and I were returning to LA the next stay, and had booked ourselves into the Beverly Hills Hotel. One afternoon, I was sitting in one of the courtyards, surrounded by flowers, squirrels jumping in the pines, that I realized I could not face going to the busy-noisy BHH, whose rooms and bathrooms I love. I asked them for a room : fully booked, they promised they would look for any opportunity.On check-out the GM discounts were there. They gracefully accepted to store most of our luggage, as we checked-in a rented Navigator for our party of 5, and checked-out in cute rented A4 convertible for the 2 of us, and we can't travel light. At that point no one knew if we would be back for a stay.They found a DL room with patio, as requested, probably the nicest of all we saw / stayed in. They even put us on a package, with free breakfast and valet parking, for less than the rack rate. Great service again, so friendly and efficient. Amazing concierge, she found a table at Cut 2 days before.It is true, still true unfirtunately, that the bathrooms litterally date back from another century, perhaps not the 20th ... It really is the only downside of that worldclass place.I can't wait to return.We'll be beck next summer. 
