<Author>A TripAdvisor Member
<Content>The best of times, the worst of times The Bel-Air is undoubtedly one of the finest 5-star hotels I have stayed at, the finest in some respects, but that is only after you find a room you that is actually liveable! The staff are in the main outstanding, the grounds and general ambience are entrancing and food and drink choices and venues excellent. That's a lot that's very good. The not necessarily good, regardless of price, are the rooms. I've stayed twice about a year apart. Both times I've immediately requested a room change on arrival. Looking for upgrades? No, looking for a room where the bedroom doesn't adjoin a major walkway or other source of significant noise (there are very many of these rooms - see review posted September 30, 2005)and where the size of the room approximates the promotional literature and photos. If you pay twice as much for a room that features a fireplace and balcony don't expect that room to be also larger than a small standard room - it won't necessarily be. When discussing the fact that room size wasn't closely correlated with price the Bel-Air staff simply pleasantly agreed and worked with me to find an acceptable room. It's either a charming eccentricity or very much not depending on where they first put you. The hotel gives you a map with room numbers, if you plan on staying again keep the map. Like the lady who posted September 30 I'm now populating mine with crosses and ticks. A final little point that the management might attend to is the concierge service. They do the job, no doubt there, but there is a tension about them (there are a few different ones)that is at odds with the general relaxed warmth or simple professional reserve of the other staff. There is also the sense that any service, no matter how small, requires a tip. I didn't find that attitude from the other staff; perhaps they need to pay their concierge staff more - helpful not hungry is a better demeanour. In many ways I love this hotel, but I'm still undecided whether it's worth it to go through the hassle of changing rooms on arrival again. 
